quoteText:
Mother thought of getting him one, to travel round with us. There was a
lady told her of a very good teacher; an American lady--perhaps you know
her--Mrs. Sanders. I think she came from Boston. She told her of this
teacher, and we thought of getting him to travel round with us. But
Randolph said he didn t want a teacher traveling round with us. He said
he wouldn t have lessons when he was in the cars. And we ARE in the cars
about half the time. There was an English lady we met in the cars--I
think her name was Miss Featherstone; perhaps you know her. She wanted
to know why I didn t give Randolph lessons--give him  instruction,  she
called it. I guess he could give me more instruction than I could give
him. He s very smart.

I really think that you had better not meddle with little American girls
that are uncultivated, as you call them. You have lived too long out of

The last! I call it the first. I have half a
mind to leave you here and go straight back to the hotel alone.
subQuotationList: ['The last!', 'I call it the first. I have half a\nmind to leave you here and go straight back to the hotel alone.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Does she never allow
you more than three days at a time? Doesn t
she give you a vacation in summer? There s no one so hard worked but
they can get leave to go off somewhere at this season. I suppose, if you
stay another day, she ll come after you in the boat. Do wait over
till Friday, and I will go down to the landing to see her arrive!
subQuotationList:
['Does she never allow
you more than three days at a time?', 'Doesn t
she give you a vacation in summer? There s no one so hard worked but
they can get leave to go off somewhere at this season. I suppose, if you
stay another day, she ll come after you in the boat. Do wait over
till Friday, and I will go down to the landing to see her arrive!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
That s not a difficult promise to make, My aunt
has taken an apartment in Rome for the winter and has already asked me
to come and see her.
subQuotationList: ['That s not a difficult promise to make,', 'My aunt\nhas taken an apartment in Rome for the winter and has already asked me\nto come and see her.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I don t want you to come for your aunt, I want you to
come for me.
subQuotationList: ['I don t want you to come for your aunt,', 'I want you to\ncome for me.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: The Americans--of the courier?
subQuotationList: ['The Americans--of the courier?']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText: Ah, happily, the courier stayed at home.
subQuotationList: ['Ah, happily,', 'the courier stayed at home.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: She went with you all alone?
subQuotationList: ['She went with you all alone?']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText: All alone.
subQuotationList: ['All alone.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: And that, is the young person whom you wanted me to know!
subQuotationList: ['And that,', 'is the young person whom you wanted me to know!']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText:
After what
happened at Vevey, I think I may certainly call upon them,
subQuotationList: ['After what\nhappened at Vevey, I think I may certainly call upon them,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
If, after what happens--at Vevey and everywhere--you desire to keep
up the acquaintance, you are very welcome. Of course a man may know
everyone. Men are welcome to the privilege!
subQuotationList: ['If, after what happens--at Vevey and everywhere--you desire to keep\nup the acquaintance, you are very welcome. Of course a man may know\neveryone. Men are welcome to the privilege!']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText: Pray what is it that happens--here, for instance?
subQuotationList: ['Pray what is it that happens--here, for instance?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
The girl goes about alone with her foreigners. As to what happens
further, you must apply elsewhere for information. She has picked up
half a dozen of the regular Roman fortune hunters, and she takes them
about to people s houses. When she comes to a party she brings with her
a gentleman with a good deal of manner and a wonderful mustache.
subQuotationList:
['The girl goes about alone with her foreigners. As to what happens
further, you must apply elsewhere for information. She has picked up
half a dozen of the regular Roman fortune hunters, and she takes them
about to people s houses. When she comes to a party she brings with her
a gentleman with a good deal of manner and a wonderful mustache.']
speaker: Mrs. Costello
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Winterbourne'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Mr. Giovanelli']]]

quoteText: And where is the mother?
subQuotationList: ['And where is the mother?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: I haven t the least idea. They are very dreadful people.
subQuotationList: ['I haven t the least idea. They are very dreadful people.']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText:
They are very ignorant--very innocent
only. Depend upon it they are not bad.
subQuotationList: ['They are very ignorant--very innocent\nonly. Depend upon it they are not bad.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
They are hopelessly vulgar, Whether or no being
hopelessly vulgar is being  bad  is a question for the metaphysicians.
They are bad enough to dislike, at any rate; and for this short life
that is quite enough.
subQuotationList:
['They are hopelessly vulgar,', 'Whether or no being
hopelessly vulgar is being  bad  is a question for the metaphysicians.
They are bad enough to dislike, at any rate; and for this short life
that is quite enough.']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText: Madame Mila!
subQuotationList: ['Madame Mila!']
speaker: The Servant

quoteText: I know you!
subQuotationList: ['I know you!']
speaker: Randolph

quoteText: I m sure you know a great many things, How is your education coming on?
subQuotationList: ['I m sure you know a great many things,', 'How is your education coming on?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Well, I
declare!
subQuotationList: ['Well, I\ndeclare!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I told you I should come, you know,
subQuotationList: ['I told you I should come, you know,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: Well, I didn t believe it,
subQuotationList: ['Well, I didn t believe it,']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I am much obliged to you,
subQuotationList: ['I am much obliged to you,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: You might have come to see me!
subQuotationList: ['You might have come to see me!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I arrived only yesterday.
subQuotationList: ['I arrived only yesterday.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: I don t believe that!
subQuotationList: ['I don t believe that!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
We ve got a bigger place than this, It s all gold on
the walls.
subQuotationList: ['We ve got a bigger place than this,', 'It s all gold on\nthe walls.']
speaker: Randolph

quoteText:
I told you if I were to bring
you, you would say something!
subQuotationList: ['I told you if I were to bring\nyou, you would say something!']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText: I told YOU!
subQuotationList: ['I told YOU!']
speaker: Randolph

quoteText: I tell YOU, sir! It IS bigger, too!
subQuotationList: ['I tell YOU, sir!', 'It IS bigger, too!']
speaker: Randolph

quoteText:
I
hope you have been well since we parted at Vevey,
subQuotationList: ['I\nhope you have been well since we parted at Vevey,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Not very well,
sir,
subQuotationList: ['Not very well,\nsir,']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText:
She s got the dyspepsia, I ve got it too. Father s got
it. I ve got it most!
subQuotationList: ['She s got the dyspepsia,', 'I ve got it too. Father s got\nit. I ve got it most!']
speaker: Randolph

quoteText:
I suffer from the liver, I think it s this
climate; it s less bracing than Schenectady, especially in the winter
season. I don t know whether you know we reside at Schenectady. I was
saying to Daisy that I certainly hadn t found any one like Dr. Davis,
and I didn t believe I should. Oh, at Schenectady he stands first; they
think everything of him. He has so much to do, and yet there was nothing
he wouldn t do for me. He said he never saw anything like my dyspepsia,
but he was bound to cure it. I m sure there was nothing he wouldn t
try. He was just going to try something new when we came off. Mr. Miller
wanted Daisy to see Europe for herself. But I wrote to Mr. Miller that
it seems as if I couldn t get on without Dr. Davis. At Schenectady he
stands at the very top; and there s a great deal of sickness there, too.
It affects my sleep.
subQuotationList:
['I suffer from the liver,', 'I think it s this
climate; it s less bracing than Schenectady, especially in the winter
season. I don t know whether you know we reside at Schenectady. I was
saying to Daisy that I certainly hadn t found any one like Dr. Davis,

stands at the very top; and there s a great deal of sickness there, too.
It affects my sleep.']
speaker: Mrs. Miller
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Winterbourne'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Randolph', 'Mrs. Miller'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Randolph', 'Mrs. Miller'], ['Daisy Miller']]]

quoteText:
Well, I must say I am disappointed, We had heard
so much about it; I suppose we had heard too much. But we couldn t help
that. We had been led to expect something different.
subQuotationList: ['Well, I must say I am disappointed,', 'We had heard\nso much about it; I suppose we had heard too much. But we couldn t help\nthat. We had been led to expect something different.']
speaker: Mrs. Miller
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Daisy Miller', 'Randolph', 'Mrs. Miller'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Randolph', 'Mrs. Miller'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Randolph', 'Mrs. Miller'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Randolph', 'Mrs. Miller']]]

quoteText: Ah, wait a little, and you will become very fond of it,
subQuotationList: ['Ah, wait a little, and you will become very fond of it,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: I hate it worse and worse every day!
subQuotationList: ['I hate it worse and worse every day!']
speaker: Randolph

quoteText: You are like the infant Hannibal,
subQuotationList: ['You are like the infant Hannibal,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: No, I ain t!
subQuotationList: ['No, I ain t!']
speaker: Randolph

quoteText: You are not much like an infant,
subQuotationList: ['You are not much like an infant,']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText:
But we have seen
places, that I should put a long way before Rome.
subQuotationList: ['But we have seen\nplaces,', 'that I should put a long way before Rome.']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText: There s Zurich, I think Zurich is lovely; and we hadn t heard half so much about it.
subQuotationList: ['There s Zurich,', 'I think Zurich is lovely; and we hadn t heard half so much about it.']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText: The best place we ve seen is the City of Richmond!
subQuotationList: ['The best place we ve seen is the City of Richmond!']
speaker: Randolph

quoteText:
He means the ship, We crossed in that ship.
Randolph had a good time on the City of Richmond.
subQuotationList: ['He means the ship,', 'We crossed in that ship.\nRandolph had a good time on the City of Richmond.']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText:
It s the best place I ve seen, Only it was turned
the wrong way.
subQuotationList: ['It s the best place I ve seen,', 'Only it was turned\nthe wrong way.']
speaker: Randolph

quoteText: Well, we ve got to turn the right way some time,
subQuotationList: ['Well, we ve got to turn the right way some time,']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText:
It s on account of the society--the society s
splendid. She goes round everywhere; she has made a great number of
acquaintances. Of course she goes round more than I do. I must say they
have been very sociable; they have taken her right in. And then she
knows a great many gentlemen. Oh, she thinks there s nothing like Rome.
Of course, it s a great deal pleasanter for a young lady if she knows
plenty of gentlemen.
subQuotationList:
['It s on account of the society--the society s
splendid. She goes round everywhere; she has made a great number of
acquaintances. Of course she goes round more than I do. I must say they
have been very sociable; they have taken her right in. And then she
knows a great many gentlemen. Oh, she thinks there s nothing like Rome.
Of course, it s a great deal pleasanter for a young lady if she knows
plenty of gentlemen.']
speaker: Mrs. Miller
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller']]]

quoteText:
I ve
been telling Mrs. Walker how mean you were!
subQuotationList: ['I ve\nbeen telling Mrs. Walker how mean you were!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: And what is the evidence you have offered?
subQuotationList: ['And what is the evidence you have offered?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Why, you were awfully mean at Vevey, You wouldn t do
anything. You wouldn t stay there when I asked you.
subQuotationList: ['Why, you were awfully mean at Vevey,', 'You wouldn t do\nanything. You wouldn t stay there when I asked you.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
My dearest young lady, have I
come all the way to Rome to encounter your reproaches?
subQuotationList: ['My dearest young lady,', 'have I\ncome all the way to Rome to encounter your reproaches?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: Just hear him say that! Did you ever hear anything so quaint?
subQuotationList: ['Just hear him say that!', 'Did you ever hear anything so quaint?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: So quaint, my dear?
subQuotationList: ['So quaint, my dear?']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText:
Well, I don t know, Mrs.
Walker, I want to tell you something.
subQuotationList: ['Well, I don t know,', 'Mrs.\nWalker, I want to tell you something.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Mother-r, I
tell you you ve got to go. Eugenio ll raise--something!
subQuotationList: ['Mother-r,', 'I\ntell you you ve got to go. Eugenio ll raise--something!']
speaker: Randolph

quoteText: I m not afraid of Eugenio,
subQuotationList: ['I m not afraid of Eugenio,']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Look
here, Mrs. Walker, you know I m coming to your party.
subQuotationList: ['Look\nhere, Mrs. Walker,', 'you know I m coming to your party.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I am delighted to hear it.
subQuotationList: ['I am delighted to hear it.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: I ve got a lovely dress!
subQuotationList: ['I ve got a lovely dress!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I am very sure of that.
subQuotationList: ['I am very sure of that.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: But I want to ask a favor--permission to bring a friend.
subQuotationList: ['But I want to ask a favor--permission to bring a friend.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I shall be happy to see any of your friends,
subQuotationList: ['I shall be happy to see any of your friends,']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: Oh, they are not my friends, I never spoke to them.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, they are not my friends,', 'I never spoke to them.']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText: It s an intimate friend of mine--Mr. Giovanelli,
subQuotationList: ['It s an intimate friend of mine--Mr. Giovanelli,']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I shall be glad to see Mr. Giovanelli,
subQuotationList: ['I shall be glad to see Mr. Giovanelli,']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText:
He s an Italian, He s a
great friend of mine; he s the handsomest man in the world--except Mr.
Winterbourne! He knows plenty of Italians, but he wants to know some
Americans. He thinks ever so much of Americans. He s tremendously
clever. He s perfectly lovely!
subQuotationList:
['He s an Italian,', 'He s a
great friend of mine; he s the handsomest man in the world--except Mr.
Winterbourne! He knows plenty of Italians, but he wants to know some
Americans. He thinks ever so much of Americans. He s tremendously
clever. He s perfectly lovely!']
speaker: Daisy Miller
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Giovanelli']], [['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Winterbourne'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Mr. Giovanelli']]]

quoteText:
I
guess we ll go back to the hotel,
subQuotationList: ['I\nguess we ll go back to the hotel,']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText: You may go back to the hotel, Mother, but I m going to take a walk,
subQuotationList: ['You may go back to the hotel, Mother, but I m going to take a walk,']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: She s going to walk with Mr. Giovanelli,
subQuotationList: ['She s going to walk with Mr. Giovanelli,']
speaker: Randolph

quoteText: I am going to the Pincio,
subQuotationList: ['I am going to the Pincio,']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: Alone, my dear--at this hour?
subQuotationList: ['Alone, my dear--at this hour?']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: I don t think it s safe, my dear,
subQuotationList: ['I don t think it s safe, my dear,']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText:
Neither do I, You ll get the fever, as sure as
you live. Remember what Dr. Davis told you!
subQuotationList: ['Neither do I,', 'You ll get the fever, as sure as\nyou live. Remember what Dr. Davis told you!']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText: Give her some medicine before she goes,
subQuotationList: ['Give her some medicine before she goes,']
speaker: Randolph

quoteText:
Mrs. Walker, you are too
perfect, I m not going alone; I am going to meet a friend.
subQuotationList: ['Mrs. Walker, you are too\nperfect,', 'I m not going alone; I am going to meet a friend.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: Your friend won t keep you from getting the fever,
subQuotationList: ['Your friend won t keep you from getting the fever,']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText: Is it Mr. Giovanelli?
subQuotationList: ['Is it Mr. Giovanelli?']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText:
Mr. Giovanelli--the beautiful
Giovanelli.
subQuotationList: ['Mr. Giovanelli--the beautiful\nGiovanelli.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: My dear young friend, don t walk off to the Pincio at this hour to meet a beautiful Italian.
subQuotationList: ['My dear young friend,', 'don t walk off to the Pincio at this hour to meet a beautiful Italian.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: Well, he speaks English,
subQuotationList: ['Well, he speaks English,']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText:
Gracious me! I don t to do anything improper.
There s an easy way to settle it. The Pincio is only a hundred yards distant; and if Mr.
Winterbourne were as polite as he pretends, he would offer to walk with
me!
subQuotationList:
['Gracious me!', 'I don t to do anything improper.
There s an easy way to settle it.', 'The Pincio is only a hundred yards distant; and if Mr.
Winterbourne were as polite as he pretends, he would offer to walk with
me!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Goodbye, Eugenio! I m going
to take a walk.
subQuotationList: ['Goodbye, Eugenio!', 'I m going\nto take a walk.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Why haven t you been to see me? You can t get out of
that.
subQuotationList: ['Why haven t you been to see me?', 'You can t get out of\nthat.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
I have had the honor of telling you that I have only just stepped out
of the train.
subQuotationList: ['I have had the honor of telling you that I have only just stepped out\nof the train.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
You must have stayed in the train a good while after it stopped! I suppose you were asleep. You
have had time to go to see Mrs. Walker.
subQuotationList: ['You must have stayed in the train a good while after it stopped!', 'I suppose you were asleep. You\nhave had time to go to see Mrs. Walker.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I knew Mrs. Walker--
subQuotationList: ['I knew Mrs. Walker--']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I know where you knew her. You knew her at Geneva. She told me so.
Well, you knew me at Vevey. That s just as good. So you ought to have
come.
subQuotationList: ['I know where you knew her. You knew her at Geneva. She told me so.\nWell, you knew me at Vevey. That s just as good. So you ought to have\ncome.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
We ve got splendid rooms at the hotel; Eugenio
says they re the best rooms in Rome. We are going to stay all winter,
if we don t die of the fever; and I guess we ll stay then. It s a great
deal nicer than I thought; I thought it would be fearfully quiet; I was
sure it would be awfully poky. I was sure we should be going round
all the time with one of those dreadful old men that explain about the
pictures and things. But we only had about a week of that, and now
I m enjoying myself. I know ever so many people, and they are all so
charming. The society s extremely select. There are all kinds--English,
and Germans, and Italians. I think I like the English best. I like their
style of conversation. But there are some lovely Americans. I never saw
anything so hospitable. There s something or other every day. There s
not much dancing; but I must say I never thought dancing was everything.
I was always fond of conversation. I guess I shall have plenty at Mrs.
Walker s, her rooms are so small.
subQuotationList:
['We ve got splendid rooms at the hotel; Eugenio
says they re the best rooms in Rome. We are going to stay all winter,
if we don t die of the fever; and I guess we ll stay then. It s a great
deal nicer than I thought; I thought it would be fearfully quiet; I was
sure it would be awfully poky. I was sure we should be going round
all the time with one of those dreadful old men that explain about the
pictures and things. But we only had about a week of that, and now

speaker: Daisy Miller
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Daisy Miller', 'Randolph', 'Mrs. Miller'], ['Eugenio'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Randolph', 'Mrs. Miller'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Randolph', 'Mrs. Miller'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Randolph', 'Mrs. Miller'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Randolph', 'Mrs. Miller'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Randolph', 'Mrs. Miller'], ['Mrs. Walker'], ['Mrs. Walker']]]

quoteText:
We had better go straight to that place in front, where
you look at the view.
subQuotationList: ['We had better go straight to that place in front,', 'where\nyou look at the view.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I certainly shall not help you to find him,
subQuotationList: ['I certainly shall not help you to find him,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: Then I shall find him without you,
subQuotationList: ['Then I shall find him without you,']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: You certainly won t leave me!
subQuotationList: ['You certainly won t leave me!']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Are you afraid you ll get lost--or run
over? But there s Giovanelli, leaning against that tree. He s staring at
the women in the carriages: did you ever see anything so cool?
subQuotationList: ['Are you afraid you ll get lost--or run\nover? But there s Giovanelli, leaning against that tree. He s staring at\nthe women in the carriages: did you ever see anything so cool?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Do you mean to speak to that
man?
subQuotationList: ['Do you mean to speak to that\nman?']
speaker: Winterbourne
referringExpression: Winterbourne looked at him a moment and then said

quoteText:
Do I mean to speak to him? Why, you don t suppose I mean to communicate
by signs?
subQuotationList: ['Do I mean to speak to him? Why, you don t suppose I mean to communicate\nby signs?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Pray understand, then, that I intend to remain
with you.
subQuotationList: ['Pray understand, then,', 'that I intend to remain\nwith you.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: Well, she s a cool one!
subQuotationList: ['Well, she s a cool one!']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: I don t like the way you say that, It s too imperious.
subQuotationList: ['I don t like the way you say that,', 'It s too imperious.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
I beg your pardon if I say it wrong. The main point is to give you an
idea of my meaning.
subQuotationList: ['I beg your pardon if I say it wrong. The main point is to give you an\nidea of my meaning.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I have never allowed a gentleman to dictate to me,
or to interfere with anything I do.
subQuotationList: ['I have never allowed a gentleman to dictate to me,\nor to interfere with anything I do.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
I think you have made a mistake, You should
sometimes listen to a gentleman--the right one.
subQuotationList: ['I think you have made a mistake,', 'You should\nsometimes listen to a gentleman--the right one.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: I do nothing but listen to gentlemen! Tell me if Mr. Giovanelli is the right one?
subQuotationList: ['I do nothing but listen to gentlemen!', 'Tell me if Mr. Giovanelli is the right one?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
No, he s not the
right one.
subQuotationList: ['No, he s not the\nright one.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
He is not a gentleman, he is only a clever imitation of one. He is a music master, or a
penny-a-liner, or a third-rate artist. D__n his good looks!
subQuotationList: ['He is not a gentleman,', 'he is only a clever imitation of one. He is a music master, or a\npenny-a-liner, or a third-rate artist. D__n his good looks!']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Nevertheless, a nice girl ought to
know!
subQuotationList: ['Nevertheless,', 'a nice girl ought to\nknow!']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
It is really too dreadful, That girl must not
do this sort of thing. She must not walk here with you two men. Fifty
people have noticed her.
subQuotationList: ['It is really too dreadful,', 'That girl must not\ndo this sort of thing. She must not walk here with you two men. Fifty\npeople have noticed her.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText:
I think it s a pity to make too much
fuss about it.
subQuotationList: ['I think it s a pity to make too much\nfuss about it.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: It s a pity to let the girl ruin herself!
subQuotationList: ['It s a pity to let the girl ruin herself!']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: She is very innocent,
subQuotationList: ['She is very innocent,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
She s very crazy! Did you ever see anything so
imbecile as her mother? After you had all left me just now, I could not
sit still for thinking of it. It seemed too pitiful, not even to attempt
to save her. I ordered the carriage and put on my bonnet, and came here
as quickly as possible. Thank Heaven I have found you!
subQuotationList:
['She s very crazy!', 'Did you ever see anything so
imbecile as her mother? After you had all left me just now, I could not
sit still for thinking of it. It seemed too pitiful, not even to attempt
to save her. I ordered the carriage and put on my bonnet, and came here
as quickly as possible. Thank Heaven I have found you!']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: What do you propose to do with us?
subQuotationList: ['What do you propose to do with us?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
To ask her to get in, to drive her about here for half an hour, so that
the world may see she is not running absolutely wild, and then to take
her safely home.
subQuotationList: ['To ask her to get in, to drive her about here for half an hour, so that\nthe world may see she is not running absolutely wild, and then to take\nher safely home.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText:
I don t think it s a very happy thought, but you
can try.
subQuotationList: ['I don t think it s a very happy thought,', 'but you\ncan try.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I am glad you admire it, Will you
get in and let me put it over you?
subQuotationList: ['I am glad you admire it,', 'Will you\nget in and let me put it over you?']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText:
Oh, no, thank you, I shall admire it much more as I see
you driving round with it.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, no, thank you,', 'I shall admire it much more as I see\nyou driving round with it.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: Do get in and drive with me!
subQuotationList: ['Do get in and drive with me!']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: That would be charming, but it s so enchanting just as I am!
subQuotationList: ['That would be charming, but it s so enchanting just as I am!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: It may be enchanting, dear child, but it is not the custom here,
subQuotationList: ['It may be enchanting, dear child, but it is not the custom here,']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText:
Well, it ought to be, then! If I didn t walk I should
expire.
subQuotationList: ['Well, it ought to be, then!', 'If I didn t walk I should\nexpire.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: You should walk with your mother, dear,
subQuotationList: ['You should walk with your mother, dear,']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: With my mother dear!
subQuotationList: ['With my mother dear!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
My mother never walked ten steps in her life.
And then, you know, I am more than five years
old.
subQuotationList: ['My mother never walked ten steps in her life.\nAnd then, you know,', 'I am more than five years\nold.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
You are old enough to be more reasonable. You are old enough, dear Miss
Miller, to be talked about.
subQuotationList: ['You are old enough to be more reasonable. You are old enough, dear Miss\nMiller, to be talked about.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText:
Talked about? What do
you mean?
subQuotationList: ['Talked about? What do\nyou mean?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: Come into my carriage, and I will tell you.
subQuotationList: ['Come into my carriage, and I will tell you.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: I don t think I want to know what you mean, I don t think I should like it.
subQuotationList: ['I don t think I want to know what you mean,', 'I don t think I should like it.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: Should you prefer being thought a very reckless girl?
subQuotationList: ['Should you prefer being thought a very reckless girl?']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: Gracious!
subQuotationList: ['Gracious!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Does Mr. Winterbourne think, that, to save my reputation, I ought to get into the
carriage?
subQuotationList: ['Does Mr. Winterbourne think,', 'that, to save my reputation, I ought to get into the\ncarriage?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
I
think you should get into the carriage.
subQuotationList: ['I\nthink you should get into the carriage.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I never heard anything so stiff! If this
is improper, Mrs. Walker, then I am all improper, and you
must give me up. Goodbye; I hope you ll have a lovely ride!
subQuotationList: ['I never heard anything so stiff! If this\nis improper, Mrs. Walker,', 'then I am all improper, and you\nmust give me up. Goodbye; I hope you ll have a lovely ride!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: Get in here, sir,
subQuotationList: ['Get in here, sir,']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: That was not clever of you,
subQuotationList: ['That was not clever of you,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
In such a case, I don t wish to be clever; I
wish to be EARNEST!
subQuotationList: ['In such a case,', 'I don t wish to be clever; I\nwish to be EARNEST!']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: Well, your earnestness has only offended her and put her off.
subQuotationList: ['Well, your earnestness has only offended her and put her off.']
speaker: Winterbourne

subQuotationList: ['It has happened very well,', 'If she is so perfectly\ndetermined to compromise herself, the sooner one knows it the better;\none can act accordingly.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: I suspect she meant no harm,
subQuotationList: ['I suspect she meant no harm,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: So I thought a month ago. But she has been going too far.
subQuotationList: ['So I thought a month ago. But she has been going too far.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: What has she been doing?
subQuotationList: ['What has she been doing?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Everything that is not done here. Flirting with any man she could pick
up; sitting in corners with mysterious Italians; dancing all the evening
with the same partners; receiving visits at eleven o clock at night. Her
mother goes away when visitors come.
subQuotationList:
['Everything that is not done here. Flirting with any man she could pick
up; sitting in corners with mysterious Italians; dancing all the evening
with the same partners; receiving visits at eleven o clock at night. Her
mother goes away when visitors come.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: But her brother, sits up till midnight.
subQuotationList: ['But her brother,', 'sits up till midnight.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
He must be edified by what he sees. I m told that at their hotel
everyone is talking about her, and that a smile goes round among all the
servants when a gentleman comes and asks for Miss Miller.
subQuotationList: ['He must be edified by what he sees. I m told that at their hotel\neveryone is talking about her, and that a smile goes round among all the\nservants when a gentleman comes and asks for Miss Miller.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: The servants be hanged!
subQuotationList: ['The servants be hanged!']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
The poor girl s
only fault, is that she is very uncultivated.
subQuotationList: ['The poor girl s\nonly fault,', 'is that she is very uncultivated.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: She is naturally indelicate,
subQuotationList: ['She is naturally indelicate,']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: Take that example this morning. How long had you known her at Vevey?
subQuotationList: ['Take that example this morning. How long had you known her at Vevey?']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: A couple of days.
subQuotationList: ['A couple of days.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Fancy, then, her making it a personal matter that you should have left
the place!
subQuotationList: ['Fancy, then, her making it a personal matter that you should have left\nthe place!']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText:
I suspect, Mrs.
Walker, that you and I have lived too long at Geneva!
subQuotationList: ['I suspect, Mrs.\nWalker, that you and I have lived too long at Geneva!']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I wished to beg you to cease your relations with Miss Miller--not to
flirt with her--to give her no further opportunity to expose herself--to
let her alone, in short.
subQuotationList: ['I wished to beg you to cease your relations with Miss Miller--not to\nflirt with her--to give her no further opportunity to expose herself--to\nlet her alone, in short.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: I m afraid I can t do that, I like her extremely.
subQuotationList: ['I m afraid I can t do that,', 'I like her extremely.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: All the more reason that you shouldn t help her to make a scandal.
subQuotationList: ['All the more reason that you shouldn t help her to make a scandal.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: There shall be nothing scandalous in my attentions to her.
subQuotationList: ['There shall be nothing scandalous in my attentions to her.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
There certainly will be in the way she takes them. But I have said what
I had on my conscience, If you wish to rejoin the
young lady I will put you down. Here, by the way, you have a chance.
subQuotationList: ['There certainly will be in the way she takes them. But I have said what\nI had on my conscience,', 'If you wish to rejoin the\nyoung lady I will put you down. Here, by the way, you have a chance.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText:
You see, I ve come all alone, I m so
frightened; I don t know what to do. It s the first time I ve ever been
to a party alone, especially in this country. I wanted to bring Randolph
or Eugenio, or someone, but Daisy just pushed me off by myself. I ain t
used to going round alone.
subQuotationList:
['You see, I ve come all alone,', 'I m so
frightened; I don t know what to do. It s the first time I ve ever been
to a party alone, especially in this country. I wanted to bring Randolph
or Eugenio, or someone, but Daisy just pushed me off by myself. I ain t
used to going round alone.']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText: And does not your daughter intend to favor us with her society?
subQuotationList: ['And does not your daughter intend to favor us with her society?']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: Well, Daisy s all dressed,
subQuotationList: ['Well, Daisy s all dressed,']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText:
She got
dressed on purpose before dinner. But she s got a friend of hers there;
that gentleman--the Italian--that she wanted to bring. They ve got going
at the piano; it seems as if they couldn t leave off. Mr. Giovanelli
sings splendidly. But I guess they ll come before very long,
subQuotationList:
['She got
dressed on purpose before dinner. But she s got a friend of hers there;
that gentleman--the Italian--that she wanted to bring. They ve got going
at the piano; it seems as if they couldn t leave off. Mr. Giovanelli
sings splendidly. But I guess they ll come before very long,']
speaker: Mrs. Miller
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Mr. Giovanelli']]]

quoteText: I m sorry she should come in that way,
subQuotationList: ['I m sorry she should come in that way,']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText:
Well, I told her that there was no use in her getting dressed before
dinner if she was going to wait three hours, I didn t see the use of her putting on such a dress as that to sit
round with Mr. Giovanelli.
subQuotationList: ['Well, I told her that there was no use in her getting dressed before\ndinner if she was going to wait three hours,', 'I didn t see the use of her putting on such a dress as that to sit\nround with Mr. Giovanelli.']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText: This is most horrible!
subQuotationList: ['This is most horrible!']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText:
Elle s affiche. It s her revenge for my having
ventured to remonstrate with her. When she comes, I shall not speak to
her.
subQuotationList: ['Elle s affiche. It s her revenge for my having\nventured to remonstrate with her. When she comes, I shall not speak to\nher.']
speaker: Mrs. Walker
referringExpression: said Mrs Walker turning away and addressing herself to Winterbourne

quoteText:
I m afraid you thought
I never was coming, so I sent mother off to tell you. I wanted to make
Mr. Giovanelli practice some things before he came; you know he sings
beautifully, and I want you to ask him to sing. This is Mr. Giovanelli;
you know I introduced him to you; he s got the most lovely voice, and
he knows the most charming set of songs. I made him go over them this
evening on purpose; we had the greatest time at the hotel.
subQuotationList:
['I m afraid you thought
I never was coming, so I sent mother off to tell you. I wanted to make

quoteText: Is there anyone I know?
subQuotationList: ['Is there anyone I know?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I think every one knows you!
subQuotationList: ['I think every one knows you!']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: It s a pity these rooms are so small; we can t dance,
subQuotationList: ['It s a pity these rooms are so small; we can t dance,']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I am not sorry we can t dance, I don t dance.
subQuotationList: ['I am not sorry we can t dance,', 'I don t dance.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Of course you don t dance; you re too stiff, I hope
you enjoyed your drive with Mrs. Walker!
subQuotationList: ['Of course you don t dance; you re too stiff,', 'I hope\nyou enjoyed your drive with Mrs. Walker!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: No. I didn t enjoy it; I preferred walking with you.
subQuotationList: ['No. I didn t enjoy it; I preferred walking with you.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
We paired off: that was much better, But did you ever
hear anything so cool as Mrs. Walker s wanting me to get into her
carriage and drop poor Mr. Giovanelli, and under the pretext that it was
proper? People have different ideas! It would have been most unkind; he
had been talking about that walk for ten days.
subQuotationList:
['We paired off: that was much better,', 'But did you ever
hear anything so cool as Mrs. Walker s wanting me to get into her
carriage and drop poor Mr. Giovanelli, and under the pretext that it was
proper? People have different ideas! It would have been most unkind; he
had been talking about that walk for ten days.']

mentionEntitiesList: [[['Daisy Miller', 'Winterbourne', 'Mr. Giovanelli', 'Mrs. Walker']], [['Winterbourne'], ['Mrs. Walker'], ['Mrs. Walker'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Mr. Giovanelli']]]

quoteText:
He should not have talked about it at all, he
would never have proposed to a young lady of this country to walk about
the streets with him.
subQuotationList: ['He should not have talked about it at all,', 'he\nwould never have proposed to a young lady of this country to walk about\nthe streets with him.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
About the streets? Where, then,
would he have proposed to her to walk? The Pincio is not the streets,
either; and I, thank goodness, am not a young lady of this country. The
young ladies of this country have a dreadfully poky time of it, so far
as I can learn; I don t see why I should change my habits for THEM.
subQuotationList:
['About the streets?', 'Where, then,
would he have proposed to her to walk? The Pincio is not the streets,
either; and I, thank goodness, am not a young lady of this country. The
young ladies of this country have a dreadfully poky time of it, so far
as I can learn; I don t see why I should change my habits for THEM.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I am afraid your habits are those of a flirt,
subQuotationList: ['I am afraid your habits are those of a flirt,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Of course they are, I m a fearful, frightful flirt! Did you ever hear of a nice girl
that was not? But I suppose you will tell me now that I am not a nice
girl.
subQuotationList: ['Of course they are,', 'I m a fearful, frightful flirt! Did you ever hear of a nice girl\nthat was not? But I suppose you will tell me now that I am not a nice\ngirl.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
You re a very nice girl; but I wish you would flirt with me, and me
only,
subQuotationList: ['You re a very nice girl; but I wish you would flirt with me, and me\nonly,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Ah! thank you--thank you very much; you are the last man I should think
of flirting with. As I have had the pleasure of informing you, you are
too stiff.
subQuotationList: ['Ah! thank you--thank you very much; you are the last man I should think\nof flirting with. As I have had the pleasure of informing you, you are\ntoo stiff.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: You say that too often,
subQuotationList: ['You say that too often,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
If I could have the sweet hope of making
you angry, I should say it again.
subQuotationList: ['If I could have the sweet hope of making\nyou angry, I should say it again.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Don t do that; when I am angry I m stiffer than ever. But if you won t
flirt with me, do cease, at least, to flirt with your friend at the
piano; they don t understand that sort of thing here.
subQuotationList: ['Don t do that; when I am angry I m stiffer than ever. But if you won t\nflirt with me, do cease, at least, to flirt with your friend at the\npiano; they don t understand that sort of thing here.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: I thought they understood nothing else!
subQuotationList: ['I thought they understood nothing else!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: Not in young unmarried women.
subQuotationList: ['Not in young unmarried women.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
It seems to me much more proper in young unmarried women than in old
married ones,
subQuotationList: ['It seems to me much more proper in young unmarried women than in old\nmarried ones,']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Well, when you deal with natives you must go
by the custom of the place. Flirting is a purely American custom;
it doesn t exist here. So when you show yourself in public with Mr.
Giovanelli, and without your mother--
subQuotationList:
['Well,', 'when you deal with natives you must go
by the custom of the place. Flirting is a purely American custom;
it doesn t exist here. So when you show yourself in public with Mr.
Giovanelli, and without your mother--']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: Gracious! poor Mother!
subQuotationList: ['Gracious! poor Mother!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Though you may be flirting, Mr. Giovanelli is not; he means something
else.
subQuotationList: ['Though you may be flirting, Mr. Giovanelli is not; he means something\nelse.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
He isn t preaching, at any rate, And if you
want very much to know, we are neither of us flirting; we are too good
friends for that: we are very intimate friends.
subQuotationList: ['He isn t preaching, at any rate,', 'And if you\nwant very much to know, we are neither of us flirting; we are too good\nfriends for that: we are very intimate friends.']
speaker: Daisy Miller
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Giovanelli']], [['Winterbourne'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Daisy Miller', 'Mr. Giovanelli']]]

quoteText:
Ah! if you are in love with each other, it is
another affair.
subQuotationList: ['Ah!', 'if you are in love with each other, it is\nanother affair.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Mr.
Giovanelli, at least, never says such very disagreeable things to me.
subQuotationList: ['Mr.\nGiovanelli, at least,', 'never says such very disagreeable things to me.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Won t you
come into the other room and have some tea?
subQuotationList: ['Won t you\ncome into the other room and have some tea?']
speaker: Mr. Giovanelli

quoteText:
It has never occurred
to Mr. Winterbourne to offer me any tea,
subQuotationList: ['It has never occurred\nto Mr. Winterbourne to offer me any tea,']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I have offered you advice,
subQuotationList: ['I have offered you advice,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: I prefer weak tea!
subQuotationList: ['I prefer weak tea!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Good night, Mrs. Walker, we ve
had a beautiful evening. You see, if I let Daisy come to parties without
me, I don t want her to go away without me.
subQuotationList: ['Good night, Mrs. Walker,', 'we ve\nhad a beautiful evening. You see, if I let Daisy come to parties without\nme, I don t want her to go away without me.']
speaker: Mrs. Miller
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mrs. Walker']], [['Daisy Miller', 'Mrs. Miller'], ['Mrs. Walker'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller']]]

quoteText: That was very cruel,
subQuotationList: ['That was very cruel,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: She never enters my drawing room again!
subQuotationList: ['She never enters my drawing room again!']
speaker: Mrs. Walker

quoteText: That s what makes you so pensive in these days, eh?
subQuotationList: ['That s what makes you so pensive in these days, eh?']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText: I had not the least idea I was pensive,
subQuotationList: ['I had not the least idea I was pensive,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: You are very much preoccupied; you are thinking of something.
subQuotationList: ['You are very much preoccupied; you are thinking of something.']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText: And what is it, that you accuse me of thinking of?
subQuotationList: ['And what is it,', 'that you accuse me of thinking of?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Of that young lady s--Miss Baker s, Miss Chandler s--what s her
name?--Miss Miller s intrigue with that little barber s block.
subQuotationList: ['Of that young lady s--Miss Baker s, Miss Chandler s--what s her\nname?--Miss Miller s intrigue with that little barber s block.']
speaker: Mrs. Costello
mentionTextsList: [['that young lady', 'her', 'Miss Miller', 'that little barber s block']]

quoteText:
Do you call it an intrigue, an affair that goes
on with such peculiar publicity?
subQuotationList: ['Do you call it an intrigue,', 'an affair that goes\non with such peculiar publicity?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: That s their folly, it s not their merit.
subQuotationList: ['That s their folly,', 'it s not their merit.']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText:
No, I don t believe that there is anything to be
called an intrigue.
subQuotationList: ['No,', 'I don t believe that there is anything to be\ncalled an intrigue.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I have heard a dozen people speak of it; they say she is quite carried
away by him.
subQuotationList: ['I have heard a dozen people speak of it; they say she is quite carried\naway by him.']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText: They are certainly very intimate,
subQuotationList: ['They are certainly very intimate,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
He is very handsome. One easily sees how it is. She thinks
him the most elegant man in the world, the finest gentleman. She has
never seen anything like him; he is better, even, than the courier.
It was the courier probably who introduced him; and if he succeeds in
marrying the young lady, the courier will come in for a magnificent
commission.
subQuotationList:
['He is very handsome. One easily sees how it is. She thinks
him the most elegant man in the world, the finest gentleman. She has
never seen anything like him; he is better, even, than the courier.
It was the courier probably who introduced him; and if he succeeds in

speaker: Mrs. Costello
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Eugenio'], ['Eugenio'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Eugenio']]]

quoteText:
I don t believe she thinks of marrying him, and I
don t believe he hopes to marry her.
subQuotationList: ['I don t believe she thinks of marrying him,', 'and I\ndon t believe he hopes to marry her.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
You may be very sure she thinks of nothing. She goes on from day to
day, from hour to hour, as they did in the Golden Age. I can imagine
nothing more vulgar. And at the same time, depend
upon it that she may tell you any moment that she is  engaged.
subQuotationList:
['You may be very sure she thinks of nothing. She goes on from day to
day, from hour to hour, as they did in the Golden Age. I can imagine
nothing more vulgar. And at the same time,', 'depend
upon it that she may tell you any moment that she is  engaged.']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText: I think that is more than Giovanelli expects,
subQuotationList: ['I think that is more than Giovanelli expects,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: Who is Giovanelli?
subQuotationList: ['Who is Giovanelli?']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText:
The little Italian. I have asked questions about him and learned
something. He is apparently a perfectly respectable little man. I
believe he is, in a small way, a cavaliere avvocato. But he doesn t
move in what are called the first circles. I think it is really not
absolutely impossible that the courier introduced him. He is evidently
immensely charmed with Miss Miller. If she thinks him the finest
gentleman in the world, he, on his side, has never found himself in
personal contact with such splendor, such opulence, such expensiveness
as this young lady s. And then she must seem to him wonderfully pretty
and interesting. I rather doubt that he dreams of marrying her. That
must appear to him too impossible a piece of luck. He has nothing but
his handsome face to offer, and there is a substantial Mr. Miller in
that mysterious land of dollars. Giovanelli knows that he hasn t a title
to offer. If he were only a count or a marchese! He must wonder at his
luck, at the way they have taken him up.
subQuotationList:
['The little Italian. I have asked questions about him and learned
something. He is apparently a perfectly respectable little man. I
believe he is, in a small way, a cavaliere avvocato. But he doesn t
move in what are called the first circles. I think it is really not
absolutely impossible that the courier introduced him. He is evidently
immensely charmed with Miss Miller. If she thinks him the finest
gentleman in the world, he, on his side, has never found himself in
personal contact with such splendor, such opulence, such expensiveness
as this young lady s. And then she must seem to him wonderfully pretty
and interesting. I rather doubt that he dreams of marrying her. That
must appear to him too impossible a piece of luck. He has nothing but
his handsome face to offer, and there is a substantial Mr. Miller in
that mysterious land of dollars. Giovanelli knows that he hasn t a title
to offer. If he were only a count or a marchese! He must wonder at his
luck, at the way they have taken him up.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
He accounts for it by his handsome face and thinks Miss Miller a young
lady qui se passe ses fantaisies!
subQuotationList: ['He accounts for it by his handsome face and thinks Miss Miller a young\nlady qui se passe ses fantaisies!']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText:
It is very true, that Daisy and her mamma have
not yet risen to that stage of--what shall I call it?--of culture at
which the idea of catching a count or a marchese begins. I believe that
they are intellectually incapable of that conception.
subQuotationList:
['It is very true,', 'that Daisy and her mamma have
not yet risen to that stage of--what shall I call it?--of culture at
which the idea of catching a count or a marchese begins. I believe that
they are intellectually incapable of that conception.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: Ah! but the avvocato can t believe it,
subQuotationList: ['Ah! but the avvocato can t believe it,']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText:
And in the same cabinet, by the way, I had the
pleasure of contemplating a picture of a different kind--that pretty
American girl whom you pointed out to me last week.
subQuotationList: ['And in the same cabinet, by the way, I had the\npleasure of contemplating a picture of a different kind--that pretty\nAmerican girl whom you pointed out to me last week.']
speaker: Winterbourne's Friend
referringExpression: His friend talked for a moment about the superb portrait of Innocent X by Velasquez which hangs in one of the cabinets of the palace and then said

quoteText: Who was her companion?
subQuotationList: ['Who was her companion?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
A little Italian with a bouquet in his buttonhole. The girl is
delightfully pretty, but I thought I understood from you the other day
that she was a young lady du meilleur monde.
subQuotationList: ['A little Italian with a bouquet in his buttonhole. The girl is\ndelightfully pretty, but I thought I understood from you the other day\nthat she was a young lady du meilleur monde.']
speaker: Winterbourne's Friend

quoteText: So she is!
subQuotationList: ['So she is!']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
She s gone out somewhere with Mr. Giovanelli, She s
always going round with Mr. Giovanelli.
subQuotationList: ['She s gone out somewhere with Mr. Giovanelli,', 'She s\nalways going round with Mr. Giovanelli.']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText: I have noticed that they are very intimate,
subQuotationList: ['I have noticed that they are very intimate,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Oh, it seems as if they couldn t live without each other! Well, he s a real gentleman, anyhow. I keep telling Daisy she s
engaged!
subQuotationList: ['Oh, it seems as if they couldn t live without each other!', 'Well, he s a real gentleman, anyhow. I keep telling Daisy she s\nengaged!']
speaker: Mrs. Miller

quoteText: And what does Daisy say?
subQuotationList: ['And what does Daisy say?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Oh, she says she isn t engaged. But she might as well be! she goes on as if she was. But I ve made Mr.
Giovanelli promise to tell me, if SHE doesn t. I should want to write to
Mr. Miller about it--shouldn t you?
subQuotationList: ['Oh, she says she isn t engaged. But she might as well be!', 'she goes on as if she was. But I ve made Mr.\nGiovanelli promise to tell me, if SHE doesn t. I should want to write to\nMr. Miller about it--shouldn t you?']
speaker: Mrs. Miller
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller']], [['Daisy Miller'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Mr. Giovanelli'], ['Daisy Miller'], ['Winterbourne']]]

quoteText: Well, I should think you would be lonesome!
subQuotationList: ['Well,', 'I should think you would be lonesome!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: Lonesome?
subQuotationList: ['Lonesome?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
You are always going round by yourself. Can t you get anyone to walk
with you?
subQuotationList: ['You are always going round by yourself. Can t you get anyone to walk\nwith you?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I am not so fortunate, as your companion.
subQuotationList: ['I am not so fortunate,', 'as your companion.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I know why you say that, Because you
think I go round too much with HIM.
subQuotationList: ['I know why you say that,', 'Because you\nthink I go round too much with HIM.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: Every one thinks so--if you care to know,
subQuotationList: ['Every one thinks so--if you care to know,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Of course I care to know! But I don t
believe it. They are only pretending to be shocked. They don t really
care a straw what I do. Besides, I don t go round so much.
subQuotationList: ['Of course I care to know!', 'But I don t\nbelieve it. They are only pretending to be shocked. They don t really\ncare a straw what I do. Besides, I don t go round so much.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I think you will find they do care. They will show it disagreeably.
subQuotationList: ['I think you will find they do care. They will show it disagreeably.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: How disagreeably?
subQuotationList: ['How disagreeably?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: Haven t you noticed anything?
subQuotationList: ['Haven t you noticed anything?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I have noticed you. But I noticed you were as stiff as an umbrella the
first time I saw you.
subQuotationList: ['I have noticed you. But I noticed you were as stiff as an umbrella the\nfirst time I saw you.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: You will find I am not so stiff as several others,
subQuotationList: ['You will find I am not so stiff as several others,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: How shall I find it?
subQuotationList: ['How shall I find it?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: By going to see the others.
subQuotationList: ['By going to see the others.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: What will they do to me?
subQuotationList: ['What will they do to me?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: They will give you the cold shoulder. Do you know what that means?
subQuotationList: ['They will give you the cold shoulder. Do you know what that means?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Do you mean as
Mrs. Walker did the other night?
subQuotationList: ['Do you mean as\nMrs. Walker did the other night?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: Exactly!
subQuotationList: ['Exactly!']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I shouldn t think
you would let people be so unkind!
subQuotationList: ['I shouldn t think\nyou would let people be so unkind!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: How can I help it?
subQuotationList: ['How can I help it?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: I should think you would say something.
subQuotationList: ['I should think you would say something.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: I do say something;
subQuotationList: ['I do say something;']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I say that your mother
tells me that she believes you are engaged.
subQuotationList: ['I say that your mother\ntells me that she believes you are engaged.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: Well, she does,
subQuotationList: ['Well, she does,']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: And does Randolph believe it?
subQuotationList: ['And does Randolph believe it?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: I guess Randolph doesn t believe anything,
subQuotationList: ['I guess Randolph doesn t believe anything,']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Since you have mentioned
it, I AM engaged.
subQuotationList: ['Since you have mentioned\nit,', 'I AM engaged.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: You don t believe!
subQuotationList: ['You don t believe!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: Yes, I believe it,
subQuotationList: ['Yes, I believe it,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: Oh, no, you don t! Well, then--I am not!
subQuotationList: ['Oh, no, you don t!', 'Well, then--I am not!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
Well, he looks at us as one of the old lions or tigers
may have looked at the Christian martyrs!
subQuotationList: ['Well, he looks at us as one of the old lions or tigers\nmay have looked at the Christian martyrs!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: Let us hope he is not very hungry, He will have to take me first; you will serve for dessert!
subQuotationList: ['Let us hope he is not very hungry,', 'He will have to take me first; you will serve for dessert!']
speaker: Mr. Giovanelli

quoteText: Why, it was Mr. Winterbourne! He saw me, and he cuts me!
subQuotationList: ['Why, it was Mr. Winterbourne! He saw me, and he cuts me!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: How long have you been here?
subQuotationList: ['How long have you been here?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
All the evening, I never saw
anything so pretty.
subQuotationList: ['All the evening,', 'I never saw\nanything so pretty.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
I am afraid, that you will not think Roman fever
very pretty. This is the way people catch it.
subQuotationList: ['I am afraid,', 'that you will not think Roman fever\nvery pretty. This is the way people catch it.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I wonder, that you, a native Roman, should countenance
such a terrible indiscretion.
subQuotationList: ['I wonder,', 'that you, a native Roman, should countenance\nsuch a terrible indiscretion.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: Ah, for myself I am not afraid.
subQuotationList: ['Ah,', 'for myself I am not afraid.']
speaker: Mr. Giovanelli

quoteText: Neither am I--for you! I am speaking for this young lady.
subQuotationList: ['Neither am I--for you! I am speaking for this young lady.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I told the
signorina it was a grave indiscretion, but when was the signorina ever
prudent?
subQuotationList: ['I told the\nsignorina it was a grave indiscretion, but when was the signorina ever\nprudent?']
speaker: Mr. Giovanelli

quoteText:
I never was sick, and I don t mean to be! I
don t look like much, but I m healthy! I was bound to see the Colosseum
by moonlight; I shouldn t have wanted to go home without that; and we
have had the most beautiful time, haven t we, Mr. Giovanelli? If there
has been any danger, Eugenio can give me some pills. He has got some
splendid pills.
subQuotationList:
['I never was sick, and I don t mean to be!', 'I
don t look like much, but I m healthy! I was bound to see the Colosseum
by moonlight; I shouldn t have wanted to go home without that; and we

quoteText:
I should advise you, to drive home as fast as
possible and take one!
subQuotationList: ['I should advise you,', 'to drive home as fast as\npossible and take one!']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
What you say is very wise, I will go and make
sure the carriage is at hand.
subQuotationList: ['What you say is very wise,', 'I will go and make\nsure the carriage is at hand.']

quoteText:
Well, I HAVE seen the Colosseum by
moonlight! That s one good thing.
subQuotationList: ['Well, I HAVE seen the Colosseum by\nmoonlight!', 'That s one good thing.']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
DID you believe I was engaged,
the other day?
subQuotationList: ['DID you believe I was engaged,\nthe other day?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText: It doesn t matter what I believed the other day,
subQuotationList: ['It doesn t matter what I believed the other day,']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: Well, what do you believe now?
subQuotationList: ['Well, what do you believe now?']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
I believe that it makes very little difference whether you are engaged
or not!
subQuotationList: ['I believe that it makes very little difference whether you are engaged\nor not!']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Quick! quick! if we get in by midnight
we are quite safe.
subQuotationList: ['Quick! quick!', 'if we get in by midnight\nwe are quite safe.']
speaker: Mr. Giovanelli

quoteText: Don t forget Eugenio s pills!
subQuotationList: ['Don t forget Eugenio s pills!']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
I don t care, whether I have
Roman fever or not!
subQuotationList: ['I don t care,', 'whether I have\nRoman fever or not!']
speaker: Daisy Miller

quoteText:
It s going round at night, that s what made her sick.
She s always going round at night. I shouldn t think she d want to,
it s so plaguy dark. You can t see anything here at night, except when
there s a moon. In America there s always a moon!
subQuotationList:
['It s going round at night,', 'that s what made her sick.
She s always going round at night. I shouldn t think she d want to,
it s so plaguy dark. You can t see anything here at night, except when
there s a moon. In America there s always a moon!']
speaker: Randolph

quoteText:
Daisy spoke of you the other day, Half the time she doesn t know what she s saying, but that time I think
she did. She gave me a message she told me to tell you. She told me to
tell you that she never was engaged to that handsome Italian. I am sure
I am very glad; Mr. Giovanelli hasn t been near us since she was taken
ill. I thought he was so much of a gentleman; but I don t call that
very polite! A lady told me that he was afraid I was angry with him for
taking Daisy round at night. Well, so I am, but I suppose he knows I m a
lady. I would scorn to scold him. Anyway, she says she s not engaged. I
don t know why she wanted you to know, but she said to me three times, And then she told me to ask if you
remembered the time you went to that castle in Switzerland. But I said
I wouldn t give any such messages as that. Only, if she is not engaged,
I m sure I m glad to know it.

['Daisy spoke of you the other day,', 'Half the time she doesn t know what she s saying, but that time I think

quoteText:
She was the most beautiful young
lady I ever saw, and the most amiable;
subQuotationList: ['She was the most beautiful young\nlady I ever saw, and the most amiable;']
speaker: Mr. Giovanelli

quoteText: and she was the most innocent.
subQuotationList: ['and she was the most innocent.']
speaker: Mr. Giovanelli

quoteText:
And the
most innocent?
subQuotationList: ['And the\nmost innocent?']
speaker: Winterbourne
referringExpression: Winterbourne looked at him and presently repeated his words

quoteText: The most innocent!
subQuotationList: ['The most innocent!']
speaker: Mr. Giovanelli

quoteText:
Why the devil, did you
take her to that fatal place?
subQuotationList: ['Why the devil,', 'did you\ntake her to that fatal place?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
For myself I had no fear; and she
wanted to go.
subQuotationList: ['For myself I had no fear; and she\nwanted to go.']
speaker: Mr. Giovanelli

quoteText: That was no reason!
subQuotationList: ['That was no reason!']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
If she had lived, I should
have got nothing. She would never have married me, I am sure.
subQuotationList: ['If she had lived, I should\nhave got nothing. She would never have married me, I am sure.']
speaker: Mr. Giovanelli

quoteText: She would never have married you?
subQuotationList: ['She would never have married you?']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText: For a moment I hoped so. But no. I am sure.
subQuotationList: ['For a moment I hoped so. But no. I am sure.']
speaker: Mr. Giovanelli

quoteText:
I am sure I don t know, How did your injustice
affect her?
subQuotationList: ['I am sure I don t know,', 'How did your injustice\naffect her?']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText:
She sent me a message before her death which I didn t understand at the
time; but I have understood it since. She would have appreciated one s
esteem.
subQuotationList: ['She sent me a message before her death which I didn t understand at the\ntime; but I have understood it since. She would have appreciated one s\nesteem.']
speaker: Winterbourne

quoteText:
Is that a modest way, of saying that she would
have reciprocated one s affection?
subQuotationList: ['Is that a modest way,', 'of saying that she would\nhave reciprocated one s affection?']
speaker: Mrs. Costello

quoteText:
You were right in that remark that you made last summer. I was booked
to make a mistake. I have lived too long in foreign parts.
subQuotationList: ['You were right in that remark that you made last summer. I was booked\nto make a mistake. I have lived too long in foreign parts.']
speaker: Winterbourne
